introduction :¶

i'm using data colleted by (TMDb)and cleaned by kaggle..it's a movie dataset containing about 10.000 movie with 20 different ascpect like releasing year and production compaines..i'm trying to explore this data ..finding the most effective elements on highest profit movies

*** Questions to answer about :¶

1-dimensions and type of data at the dataset

2-what are the top 10 produced genres?

3-what are the top 10 popular movies?

4-what are the top 10 runtime movies?

5-what is the average runtime?

6-what are the top 10 profit movies?

7-what is the highest profit movie ?

8-what is the higest revenue movie?

9-what is the highest budget movie?

10-what are the top 20 production companies?

11-what are the top 10 movie directors?

12-what are the number of prodcued movie per year till 2014?

13-what is the most common produced genres per year ?

## bulding a function to find good and bad profit 

def profit(profit):
    if profit <= 0 :
        return "bad"
    else:
        return "good"
    
data["profit_scale"]=data["profit"].apply(profit)

##visualzing good and bad movies at profit using countplot from seaborn 
 
sns.set_theme(style="darkgrid")
sns.countplot(x=data["profit_scale"])
plt.title("num of good and bad movies")
plt.show()

5- Conclusion¶

  • The highest movie at profit is "star wars"

  • The most common produced genre is "comedy"

  • The highest profit movie is not the highest movie at revenue or even budget

  • The most common producing companies are "Universal Studios"&'Paramount Pictures'

  • "Woody Allen" is the most common director

  • The average runtime for the movie till 2015 is 102 min

limitations¶

data were orginally cleaned by kaggle so this dataset might be biased .i used budget_adgj and revenue_adj columns cuz taxes are included in those columns."lots of missing data " there is around 1000 movie that doesn't have a name for a production company also there is 44 movie that deosn't have a director name.
